solution:
class AsyncQueue {
  private concurrency: number;
  private running = 0;
  private paused = false;
  private queue: Array<() => void> = [];
  private idleWaiters: Array<() => void> = [];

  constructor(concurrency: number) {
    this.concurrency = Math.max(1, concurrency);
  }

  enqueue<T>(task: () => Promise<T>): Promise<T> {
    return new Promise<T>((resolve, reject) => {
      this.queue.push(() => {
        this.running++;
        task()
          .then(resolve, reject)
          .finally(() => {
            this.running--;
            this.notifyIfIdle();
            this.process();
          });
      });
      this.process();
    });
  }

  pause(): void {
    this.paused = true;
  }

  resume(): void {
    this.paused = false;
    this.process();
  }

  waitAll(): Promise<void> {
    return new Promise(resolve => {
      if (this.isIdle()) {
        resolve();
      } else {
        this.idleWaiters.push(resolve);
      }
    });
  }

  private isIdle(): boolean {
    return this.running === 0 && this.queue.length === 0;
  }

  private notifyIfIdle(): void {
    if (this.isIdle()) {
      this.idleWaiters.forEach(resolve => resolve());
      this.idleWaiters = [];
    }
  }

  private process(): void {
    while (!this.paused && this.running < this.concurrency && this.queue.length > 0) {
      const run = this.queue.shift()!;
      run();
    }
  }
}

description.en:
Implement a `CancellablePromise` class that wraps native `Promise` behavior with cancellation support via `AbortController`/`AbortSignal`, including optional auto-cancellation after a timeout.

**Requirements:**
- The executor receives `(resolve, reject, signal)`, where `signal` is an `AbortSignal` the executor can listen to for cleanup
- `cancel()` rejects the promise with a `CancelledError` and fires the abort signal
- An optional constructor `timeout` (ms) auto-cancels if the promise hasn't settled by then
- `isCancelled()` reports cancellation state
- Calling `cancel()` on an already-settled (resolved/rejected) or already-cancelled promise is a no-op
- Works with `await`/`.then()`/`.catch()` like a normal promise

**Class signature:**
```typescript
class CancelledError extends Error {}

type CancellableExecutor<T> = (
  resolve: (value: T) => void,
  reject: (reason?: unknown) => void,
  signal: AbortSignal
) => void;

class CancellablePromise<T> extends Promise<T> {
  constructor(executor: CancellableExecutor<T>, timeout?: number);
  cancel(): void;
  isCancelled(): boolean;
}
```

**Example:**
```typescript
const cp = new CancellablePromise<string>((resolve, reject, signal) => {
  const id = setTimeout(() => resolve('done'), 1000);
  signal.addEventListener('abort', () => clearTimeout(id));
});

setTimeout(() => cp.cancel(), 500);

try {
  await cp;
} catch (e) {
  console.log(e instanceof CancelledError, cp.isCancelled()); // true true
}
```

**Edge cases:**
- Cancelling a promise that already resolved must not throw and must not change its resolved value
- Calling `cancel()` twice has the same effect as once
- A timeout that fires after the promise already settled must be a no-op (no unhandled rejection)
- The `signal` must actually fire `'abort'` so executor-side cleanup (like `clearTimeout`) runs

description.ru:
Реализуйте класс `CancellablePromise`, оборачивающий поведение нативного `Promise` возможностью отмены через `AbortController`/`AbortSignal`, включая опциональную автоотмену по таймауту.

**Требования:**
