solution:
class CancelledError extends Error {
  constructor(message: string = 'Promise was cancelled') {
    super(message);
    this.name = 'CancelledError';
  }
}

type CancellableExecutor<T> = (
  resolve: (value: T) => void,
  reject: (reason?: unknown) => void,
  signal: AbortSignal
) => void;

class CancellablePromise<T> extends Promise<T> {
  private controller: AbortController;
  private settled = false;
  private cancelled = false;
  private rejectRef!: (reason?: unknown) => void;

  constructor(executor: CancellableExecutor<T>, timeout?: number) {
    const controller = new AbortController();
    let rejectRef!: (reason?: unknown) => void;

    super((resolve, reject) => {
      rejectRef = reject;
      const guardedResolve = (value: T) => {
        if (!this.settled) {
          this.settled = true;
          resolve(value);
        }
      };
      const guardedReject = (reason?: unknown) => {
        if (!this.settled) {
          this.settled = true;
          reject(reason);
        }
      };
      try {
        executor(guardedResolve, guardedReject, controller.signal);
      } catch (error) {
        guardedReject(error);
      }
    });

    this.controller = controller;
    this.rejectRef = rejectRef;

    if (timeout !== undefined && timeout > 0) {
      setTimeout(() => this.cancel(), timeout);
    }
  }

  cancel(): void {
    if (this.settled || this.cancelled) {
      return;
    }
    this.cancelled = true;
    this.settled = true;
    this.controller.abort();
    this.rejectRef(new CancelledError());
  }

  isCancelled(): boolean {
    return this.cancelled;
  }
}

description.en:
Implement a lightweight `Observable` class (a simplified RxJS-style stream) supporting lazy, multi-subscriber emission with chainable operators.

**Requirements:**
- The constructor takes a `subscribe` function that receives an `Observer` and returns a cleanup function
- Nothing runs until `.subscribe()` is called (lazy evaluation) — creating an Observable must have zero side effects
- Each call to `.subscribe()` re-runs the source independently (multiple subscribers don't share state or interfere)
- Chainable operators: `.map(fn)`, `.filter(predicate)`, `.take(count)`, `.catchError(handler)`
- `.take(count)` must unsubscribe from the source as soon as `count` values have been emitted, not just stop forwarding them
- `subscribe()` returns a `Subscription` with `.unsubscribe()` that stops further emissions and runs the source's cleanup

**Class signature:**
```typescript
interface Observer<T> {
  next?: (value: T) => void;
  error?: (error: Error) => void;
  complete?: () => void;
}
interface Subscription {
  unsubscribe(): void;
}

class Observable<T> {
  constructor(subscribeFn: (observer: Required<Observer<T>>) => () => void);
  subscribe(observer: Partial<Observer<T>>): Subscription;
  map<U>(fn: (value: T) => U): Observable<U>;
  filter(predicate: (value: T) => boolean): Observable<T>;
  take(count: number): Observable<T>;
  catchError(handler: (error: Error) => Observable<T>): Observable<T>;
}
```

**Example:**
```typescript
const source = new Observable<number>(observer => {
  observer.next(1); observer.next(2); observer.next(3); observer.complete();
  return () => {};
});

const out: number[] = [];
source.filter(x => x > 1).map(x => x * 10).take(1)
  .subscribe({ next: v => out.push(v), complete: () => out.push(-1) });

console.log(out); // [20, -1]
```

**Edge cases:**
- `take(0)` completes immediately without emitting or subscribing to the source at all
- Two independent `.subscribe()` calls on the same operator chain must not share emission state (e.g. two separate `take(1)` counters)
- An error thrown inside a `map`/`filter` callback must route to the observer's `error`, not throw synchronously out of `next()`
- Calling `.unsubscribe()` during emission (from inside a `next` callback) must not throw or cause further emissions on that subscription

description.ru:
Реализуйте облегчённый класс `Observable` (упрощённый RxJS-подобный поток) с ленивым, независимым для каждого подписчика испусканием значений и цепочкой операторов.

**Требования:**
- Конструктор принимает функцию `subscribe`, получающую `Observer` и возвращающую функцию очистки
- Ничего не выполняется до вызова `.subscribe()` (ленивое вычисление) — создание Observable не должно иметь побочных эффектов
- Каждый вызов `.subscribe()` независимо перезапускает источник (несколько подписчиков не делят состояние и не мешают друг другу)
- Цепочные операторы: `.map(fn)`, `.filter(predicate)`, `.take(count)`, `.catchError(handler)`
- `.take(count)` должен отписываться от источника, как только испущено `count` значений, а не просто перестать их пробрасывать
- `subscribe()` возвращает `Subscription` с `.unsubscribe()`, останавливающим дальнейшее испускание и выполняющим очистку источника

**Сигнатура класса:**
```typescript
interface Observer<T> {
  next?: (value: T) => void;
  error?: (error: Error) => void;
  complete?: () => void;
}
