class TokenBucket {
  private tokens: number;
  private lastRefill: number;

  constructor(private capacity: number, private refillPerSecond: number) {
    this.tokens = capacity;
    this.lastRefill = Date.now();
  }

  private refill(): void {
    const now = Date.now();
    const elapsedSeconds = (now - this.lastRefill) / 1000;
    if (elapsedSeconds > 0) {
      this.tokens = Math.min(this.capacity, this.tokens + elapsedSeconds * this.refillPerSecond);
      this.lastRefill = now;
    }
  }

  tryConsume(cost: number = 1): boolean {
    this.refill();
    if (this.tokens >= cost) {
      this.tokens -= cost;
      return true;
    }
    return false;
  }

  async waitForToken(cost: number = 1): Promise<void> {
    if (cost > this.capacity) {
      throw new Error('cost exceeds bucket capacity; can never be satisfied');
    }
    while (!this.tryConsume(cost)) {
      this.refill();
      const missing = cost - this.tokens;
      const waitMs = Math.max(10, (missing / this.refillPerSecond) * 1000);
      await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, waitMs));
    }
  }
}

description.en:
Implement `runTasks`, which executes a set of named async tasks that depend on each other, running independent tasks concurrently while respecting dependency order — a topological sort combined with concurrent execution.

**Requirements:**
- Input is a map of task name → `{ deps: string[], run: () => Promise<T> }`
- A task only starts once *all* of its dependencies have successfully completed
- Tasks with no unmet dependencies run concurrently (not one at a time)
- Detect circular dependencies (e.g. A depends on B, B depends on A) and reject with a descriptive error instead of hanging forever
- Resolve with a map of task name → result once every task has completed
- If any task rejects, stop scheduling *new* tasks and reject the overall result with that task's error (tasks already in flight are allowed to finish)

**Function signature:**
```typescript
interface TaskDef<T> {
  deps: string[];
  run: () => Promise<T>;
}

function runTasks<T>(tasks: Record<string, TaskDef<T>>): Promise<Record<string, T>>
```

**Example:**
```typescript
const results = await runTasks({
  fetchUser:  { deps: [], run: async () => 'user' },
  fetchPosts: { deps: [], run: async () => 'posts' },
  render:     { deps: ['fetchUser', 'fetchPosts'], run: async () => 'rendered' }
});
// fetchUser and fetchPosts run concurrently; render starts only after both finish
// results === { fetchUser: 'user', fetchPosts: 'posts', render: 'rendered' }
```

**Edge cases:**
- A task depending on a name that doesn't exist in the input map
- A circular dependency chain of any length (not just direct A→B→A, but A→B→C→A)
- Tasks with zero dependencies (must start immediately, in parallel with each other)
- One task failing shouldn't prevent already-running independent tasks from completing normally

